post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_10053113_10053254_3": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "section_id": 2290}}, "n3337": {"so_10053113_10053254_3": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "section_id": 2277}}, "n4659": {"so_10053113_10053254_3": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "section_id": 2563}}}, "10053113": {"ViewCount": "3826", "Body": "<p>It says <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B11#Type_long_long_int\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a> and <a href=\"http://www2.research.att.com/~bs/C++0xFAQ.html#long-long\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a> that type <code>long long</code> is at least as long as an <code>int</code> and has <strong>no fewer than 64 bits</strong>. I have been looking at the C++11 standard \u00a73.9.1 Fundamental Types section and I cannot find any reference to 64 bits. All I can find is that it is at least as long at <code>long int</code>, which is at least as long as <code>int</code>. The standard lists <code>long long</code> as a <em>standard</em> integer type, as opposed to an <em>extended</em> one, so I am wondering whether this assertion that <code>long long</code> holds at least 64 bits is true. And if it is, where is it stated?\nPlease note that I am talking about C++11 standard <code>long long</code> only.</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "10053254", "Title": "Is C++11's long long really at least 64 bits?", "CreationDate": "2012-04-07T08:49:29.490", "Id": "10053113", "CommentCount": "5", "FavoriteCount": "6", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2014-10-11T15:27:38.663", "Score": "35", "OwnerUserId": "661519", "Tags": "<c++><c++11>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "10053254": {"Id": "10053254", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The C++ standard references the C standard for this, see [c.limits]. <code>LLONG_MAX</code> is defined in <code>&lt;climits&gt;</code> with the same meaning as C's <code>&lt;limits.h&gt;</code>'s <code>LLONG_MAX</code>. And this is what C has to say:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_10053113_10053254_0\"><strong>5.2.4.2.1 Sizes of integer types <code>&lt;limits.h&gt;</code></strong></p>\n<p id=\"so_10053113_10053254_1\">The values given below shall be replaced by constant expressions suitable for use in <code>#if</code> preprocessing directives. [...] Their implementation-defined values shall be equal or greater in magnitude (absolute value) to those shown, with the same sign.</p>\n<p id=\"so_10053113_10053254_2\">[...]</p>\n<p id=\"so_10053113_10053254_3\">-- maximum value for an object of type <code>long long int</code></p>\n<p id=\"so_10053113_10053254_4\"><code>LLONG_MAX +9223372036854775807 //</code> 2<sup>63</sup> -1</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>A signed type that must be capable of representing the value <code>9223372036854775807</code> requires 64 bits or more.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "743382", "LastActivityDate": "2014-10-11T15:27:38.663", "Score": "35", "CreationDate": "2012-04-07T09:17:23.673", "ParentId": "10053113", "CommentCount": "4", "OwnerUserId": "743382", "LastEditDate": "2014-10-11T15:27:38.663"}});